2471,IssuesEvent,2017-09-13 00:03:40+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,7134353,88manpreet,,,opened,Seek method returning incorrect messages,[],[],0,"While using seek method of `kafka.consumer.group.seek' for a given partition, offset, we are seeing the inconsistent behavior for the messages returned with the subsequent poll method.
The issue is easily reproducible for the given topic (compacted).

Part of Workflow: 
```
from kafka.consumer.group import KafkaConsumer

topic_partition = TopicPartition(topic, 0)
consumer = KafkaConsumer(*consumer_config)
consumer.assign([topic_partition]) 
start_offset = 100 # Example value: highwatermark - 10
 
with consumer:
    consumer.seek(partition=topic_partition, offset=start_offset)
    messages = consumer.poll(timeout_ms=1000, max_records=1)[topic_partition]
    message = messages[0]
    print('Offset found:', message.offset, 'Expected offset:', start_offset)

Output:
$ Offset found:80 Expected offset:100
```


Observation:
* If iterator interface is used instead of poll interface, the issue no longer exists. My guess is somewhere while polling for messages, the fetched offsets are not updated or fetched messages are not skipped.
* At times it does give correct messages (especially when given offset is closer to highwatermark)

Please let me know if any other details are required.
",{},{}
2473,IssuesEvent,2016-05-11 10:11:59+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,9044124,sibiryakov,,,opened,Production and consumption doesn't work when used in parallel,[],[],0,"Hi guys,
the code below doesn't work. I'm probably doing something wrong, but I couldn't make it to work.
Kafka-python version is 1.1.1
and Kafka is 0.8.2.2.

```python
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
from kafka import KafkaConsumer, KafkaProducer, TopicPartition


def test_it():
    producer = KafkaProducer(bootstrap_servers=""localhost:9092"")
    consumer = KafkaConsumer(bootstrap_servers=""localhost:9092"", consumer_timeout_ms=100)
    consumer.assign([TopicPartition(""frontera-todo"", 0)])

    producer.send(""frontera-todo"", value=""11asdhey all"")
    producer.flush()

    m = next(consumer)
    
    assert m.topic == ""frontera-todo"" and m.value == ""11asdhey all""

    producer.close()
    consumer.close()

test_it()
```

If you add this consumption attempt before ``producer.send``, then it starts to work.
```python
    try:
        m = next(consumer)
    except StopIteration:
        pass
```

Could you please explain me what's going on in this code and suggest the right way of producing/consuming from the same process.",{},{}
2475,IssuesEvent,2017-01-09 19:44:55+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,405522,braedon,,,closed,Support for closing a consumer without auto-committing offsets,[],[],3,"When I destroy a consumer I want to be able to call `close()` on it so it is removed from the consumer group (without having to wait for the session timeout). 

Calling close triggers a offset commit when using auto-commit, which assumes you have finished processing all messages you have retrieved via `poll()` or the iterator. However, if you are closing the consumer due to an error or interrupt you may not have finished processing the last message(s).

There doesn't seem to be a way to close the consumer without committing offsets when using auto-commit.",{},{}
2483,IssuesEvent,2016-04-13 08:10:30+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,4892260,Poogles,,,closed,Help: Discrepancy between kafka.consumer.fetcher and KafkaConsumer,[],[],8,"We seem to be losing messages in flight between kafka.consumer.fetcher._handle_fetch_response and the KafkaConsumer API.

```Apr 06 08:43:38 host bash[20676]: DEBUG:kafka.conn:<BrokerConnection host=kafka-1 port=9092> Response 115022: FetchResponse(topics=[(topics='click', partitions=[(partition=8, error_code=0, highwater_offset=82313, message_set=[(offset=82312, message_size=433, message=(crc=-261609733, magic=0, attributes=2, key=None, value=b'\x82SNAPPY\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x01\x8f\xbe\x03\x00\x00\x01\x01\x90\x01A\x88\x00\x00\x01\xb2\x1dv\xc4\t\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xff\x00\x00\x01\xa4{MESSAGE}'))])])])
