4429,IssuesEvent,2016-11-25 18:51:17+00:00,24561828,gunthercox/ChatterBot,18617708,vishnu-ks,,,opened,Suggestion to make change in corpus data so that it can improve accuracy,[],[],0,"I just made a chatbot with training data that I made by my own. It is trained with a set of conversation about animals which we see commonly. The only problem that what I found is most of the time when we ask the bot which it don't know it will reply an answer which has closest match.
Suppose I am asking the bot 'what is a cat' and it know the response for' what is a rat' only then it reply the answer for what is a rat. So the answer which is given by the bot become entirely wrong. I tried using LowConfidence adapter to tackle with this issue and then I realized I will not be able to get the auto correction feature that currently AIML don't have if I filter response with Low confidence adapter. By auto correction what I meant is sometimes we write 'wat' instead of what, dat instead of 'that' etc. all this can be managed correctly by using closest match adapter. 
So as a solution for all this problem what I was thinking was like if we have a json file of following format as a training set, can we go through each node for searching for keyword and if a keyword is found then can we stick on that specific list of conversation to  find out a closest match response?
{
	""cow"": [
		""What is a cow?"",
		""Cow is a domestic animal""
	],

	""cat"": [
		""What is a cat?"",
		""Cat is a pet""
	]
}

Suppose I am asking a question **""what is a cat""** after removing the stopwords or by tokenizing each word we can search and find a node which has a best match and can find a response for the question from the list of corresponding node. Can we do like that? ",{},{}
