5682,IssuesEvent,2018-04-20 19:56:56+00:00,8272640,kvesteri/sqlalchemy-utils,20749,jcassee,,,opened,Why canonicalize result values using closed interval?,[],[],0,"A PostgreSQL `DateRange(datetime.date(2018, 1, 1), datetime.date(2018, 2, 1), '[)')` is loaded from the database as a `DateInterval('[2018-01-01, 2018-01-31]')`. This is because `canonicalize(value, True, True)` is called when `step` is set (which is set to a day in the case of a date range).

I know I can canonicalize the value back again to a closed/open interval, but why do this at all? Why not allow the SQL range be authoritative with regard to the endpoint mode?

If you agree, would you accept a PR that makes a change here? For example, make the call to `canonicalize_result_value` optional or set the ""canonical endpoint modes"" for a Range instance?",{},{}
