7621,IssuesEvent,2015-08-26 19:07:56+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1821014,krancour,6117407,deis,opened,Do we need a more sophisticated health check for deis-router?,[],[],0,"This is unrelated to application health checks.

On each platform we support, load balancers are configured with a health check that just tests whether anything is listening on port 80.  This means any node in a Deis cluster that is running the `deis-router` reports back as ""healthy"" and is therefore included in that load balancer's pool of instances it can send traffic to.

Where this breaks down is the case where Kubernetes is the scheduler.  If the `deis-kube-proxy` component should fail on any given machine, then the consequence is that even though a router instance might be alive and well on that same machine, application traffic sent to that machine will never reach a pod.

Is it possible that `deis-router` should include a more sophisticated health check endpoint where a 200 is returned if the router is _able_ to route traffic?  Here, ""able"" is probably defined as the `deis-router` component is up and healthy, _and_, if applicable, `deis-kube-proxy` is as well.

Ping @bacongobbler for thoughts.",{},{}
7625,IssuesEvent,2015-04-21 16:22:40+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,73019,mboersma,6117407,deis,closed,Proposal: Admins can create new users,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/controller', 'name': 'controller', 'color': 'fbca04'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],6,"We currently have the ability to [disable user registration](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/operational_tasks/#disabling-user-registration) entirely, but a common scenario is that admin users want to be able to create users, but to disallow just anyone from creating an account.

The proposal is to have three registration permission modes:
* Users can register themselves (the default)
* No users can register (`registrationEnabled`, which we currently have)
* Only admins can create user accounts (`registrationByAdminOnly` or something similar)

These could even be collapsed into one setting called something like `registrationMode`. ",{},{}
