8580,IssuesEvent,2018-02-16 21:03:48+00:00,54189815,blue-yonder/turbodbc,8329826,MathMagique,6234170,blue-yonder,closed, [SAP][ODBC Driver]Invalid attribute value,"[{'id': 543526769, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/blue-yonder/turbodbc/labels/compatibility', 'name': 'compatibility', 'color': 'b60205', 'default': False}]",[],5,"I am connecting to SAP IQ via SQLAnywhere17 ODBC driver.  This combination is not officially supported by turbodbc, but I would still like to get it to work. isql works fine, I can connect and query tables.  I can also access the database via [https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sqlanydb/](url), but it is very slow. I was able to query a few tables with turbodbc, which was very fast with the default configuration, but the great majority of them fails 

<pre>
Error: ODBC error
state: HY024
native error code: 0
message: [SAP][ODBC Driver]Invalid attribute value
</pre>

I could not find any patterns common to the tables that work (5% of the database), and that don't.  Any hints what I can try?   ",{},{}
8633,IssuesEvent,2017-10-25 00:37:12+00:00,63484632,facebookresearch/fastText,1716488,cpuhrsch,16943930,facebookresearch,reopened,-Nan(Ind) Sentence Vector,[],[],2,"Hello,

I'm using fastText and I'm getting, for a document, a vector full of -nan(ind) when I use the option print-sentence-vector. However, if I ask for the vector of each word, with print-sentence-vector, all the words have a numerical vector. Which could be the problem? Any idea, where to look for, in order to give you a better description of the problem?

The fastText model was trained by me (using the unsupervised method) with 300 dimensions. The document has 3478 words.",{},{}
8681,IssuesEvent,2018-03-19 13:24:22+00:00,63484632,facebookresearch/fastText,15029054,cryoff,16943930,facebookresearch,opened,Question on exported ngram embeddings,[],[],0,"Hello! I have a question about the ngram embeddings.
I have been trying to import embeddings into my java program. In order to do so, I first used a solution given in #289
However, when I import those ngram vectors, I can't get the embedding for ""weird"" OOV ngrams/words.
For example, I can't get the vector for 'a^3'. (using German model trained on Wikipedia) inside my app.

However, when I use fasttext directly using the same model, I get the embedding vector.
So, is there something off with the ngram embedding extraction procedure?
Also, when I try to search for 'a^3' in the list of all exported ngrams (len: 3..6), I can't find it. So, it is a bit of magic for me to understand, how embedding for 'a^3' is constructed. According to c++ code, this ngram is indeed in the dictionary..",{},{}
8687,IssuesEvent,2016-05-25 10:06:34+00:00,20493628,G-Node/nixpy,2369197,achilleas-k,574778,G-Node,opened,optGroup for H5Py backend,[],[],0,"Implement on-demand group creation in the Python backend.
Currently, groups that act as containers, such as `data_arrays` and `multi_tags`, are created along with the [parent object](https://github.com/achilleas-k/nixpy/blob/40a85ce9cd2cf1b2998735122a998e7779cb3a26/nixio/pycore/block.py#L26).
Implement [`optGroup`](https://github.com/G-Node/nix/blob/master/backend/hdf5/h5x/H5Group.hpp#L237) to create these on demand, as is done in the NIX C++ library.",{},{}
