8943,IssuesEvent,2017-04-27 07:18:09+00:00,66922106,frictionlessdata/datapackage-pipelines,3993,brew,5912125,frictionlessdata,closed,Test helpers for low-level processors,[],"[{'login': 'brew', 'id': 3993, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/3993?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/brew', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/brew/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Basic processor testing is provided for in datapackage-pipelines ([lib_test_helpers](https://github.com/frictionlessdata/datapackage-pipelines/blob/master/datapackage_pipelines/utilities/lib_test_helpers.py#L14)) using fixtures. But because the processor is run in a python subprocess, it's difficult to apply mocking for dynamic data such as dates, or the results of calls to external api services.

It would be useful if datapackage-pipelines provided the boilerplate for setting up a test that mocks `ingest` and `spew`, so processor code can be tested and relevant parts mocked out. So when our processor under test calls `ingest` it receives what we pass it in the test, and when it calls `spew` it populates a return values from `test_processor` that we can run asserts against.

```python
@mock.patch('datetime.datetime')
test_my_great_processor(mock_date):
    mock_date.side_effect = datetime.datetime.now()
    ingest_tuple = (some_params, a_datapackage, [])

    spew_results = test_processor(great_processor, ingest_tuple)
    
    # assert against spew_results here
```",{},{}
8975,IssuesEvent,2015-01-03 01:07:51+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,520669,dhermes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,Update Key API to be more user-friendly per design doc discussion,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/datastore', 'name': 'datastore', 'color': '0052cc'}]",[],2,"Related ~~to #3 and~~
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xKw8Tz6lfN5uOcv0my4uUgFSeDoRzwCLho2UGlBpqDU/edit

Plan to make this work:
- [x] Remove `Key.from_path` (since will be new constructor) (#456)
- [x] Remove all setters (#458)
- [x] Make `parent` re-use an instance (since immutable) (#459)
- [x] Make `Key` constructor act like `Key.from_path` (#460)
- [x] Make `Key.complete_key` method (needs better name) to act like `Key.id(new_id)` (#461)
- [x] Implement `Key.compare_to_proto` to check a key against a retrieved key (needs better name) (#462)
- [x] Require `dataset_id` on `Key` (may require removing `dataset_id` from `Key protos) (#463)
- [x] Add `parent` to constructor (#476)
- [x] ~~Update docstrings and other docs to reflect changes (including `__repr__`, probably shouldn't have `path`)~~ (Putting off bulk doc fixes until API is stable again)
- [x] ~~Change `Entity` constructor to only accept a `key`. (This can probably move to a new bug, which I have yet to file.)~~ (filed #484)",{},{}
