9380,IssuesEvent,2016-10-05 16:39:23+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,14370660,AC130USpectre,7388996,jupyter,opened,Saving untrusted files.,[],[],0,"Hello everyone. Sorry for asking here, I don't know where I can find an answer. I am a newb in using python 3.5.2 and Jupyter Notebook. I have some classes about python now, and our teacher delivers to us *.ipynb files with code. So, I am able to watch this files and even run cells. But I can't save them. Any new file from my teacher web-page, provided by jupyter, just don't save. I thought that it's because of firewall or antivirus software, but I was wrong. If I create a new file using jupyter, then it can be saved automatically or manually without any troubles. But when I copy content from teachers files to a new file (created by me), it don't allows me to save modified file. I also notice that there is a ""trust"" property: jupyter can trust or not trust to some files. So, when I load my teacher files, jupyter wrote into console ""Notebook %filename% is not trusted"", and I cannot save it. But when I load file, created by me, jupyter wrote into console ""Notebook %filename% is trusted"" and I can save this file. I cannot realise how he recognize untrusted files. Maybe I just may change some property to force jupyter trust any files? Or maybe I must change some properties inside *.ipynb files and my Notebook will trust them? The option File -> Trust Notebook already don't work -- it changes nothing.
Looking forward for any answer, advice, etc. Thanks!",{},{}
