10510,IssuesEvent,2015-06-24 00:30:11+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,1883523,kwlzn,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,BUILD file parsing: calls to six.exec_ can be ~47x more expensive than a likewise exec call,[],[],0,"this showed up as a hot section in some of our profiling. the following benchmark summarizes the crux of the issue:

  $ python2.7 -m timeit -n 100000 -s ""import six; code = compile('o = object()', '<string>', 'exec')"" 'six.exec_(code, {})'
  100000 loops, best of 3: 33.2 usec per loop

  $ python2.7 -m timeit -n 100000 -s ""code = compile('o = object()', '<string>', 'exec')"" 'exec(code, {})'
  100000 loops, best of 3: 0.706 usec per loop

looking at the code, six performs a double/nested exec of an uncompiled code block sort of like this:

  $ python2.7 -m timeit -n 100000 -s ""code = compile('o = object()', '<string>', 'exec')"" 'exec(""exec code in {}"")'
  100000 loops, best of 3: 23.4 usec per loop

anecdotally speaking this slowness seems to be magnified on older CPU platforms and is roughly ~26x slower on the newest haswell-gen machine. I would file an issue against six, but it looks like there are already plans to deprecate exec_ as well as existing desire to eliminate the double exec as part of https://bitbucket.org/gutworth/six/issue/126/deprecate-exec_

based on #126 and the article linked therein, it doesn't actually look like six is needed for exec() compatibility across python versions. suggest we eliminate the usage of this in build_file_parser.py:BuildFileParser:parse_build_file for an easy speedup.",{},{}
10521,IssuesEvent,2018-07-24 15:38:26+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,1131704,illicitonion,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,runtime_classpath product is populated unconditionally for all zinc compiles,[],"[{'login': 'dotordogh', 'id': 28027359, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjI4MDI3MzU5', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/28027359?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/dotordogh', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/dotordogh/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Currently we populate the `runtime_classpath` in a batch before doing all compiles: https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/d748a10adabca8bc710563a3903d1c92536de402/src/python/pants/backend/jvm/tasks/jvm_compile/jvm_compile.py#L383-L386

I'm about to make it so that this adding sometimes also contains a `DirectoryDigest`. In order to do this, it would be useful if we did this adding closer to where the compile happens, rather than up-front. It would also be useful if the replacement at https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/d748a10adabca8bc710563a3903d1c92536de402/src/python/pants/backend/jvm/tasks/jvm_compile/jvm_compile.py#L399-L406 happened close to where the compile happens (so that we can replace properly with the right `DirectoryDigest`), rather than in a blunt batch.

Ideally, this would happen inside the `Job` in the `ExecutionGraph` (https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/d748a10adabca8bc710563a3903d1c92536de402/src/python/pants/backend/jvm/tasks/jvm_compile/jvm_compile.py#L667-L726), but it's possible that won't work for multiprocess reasons.

Note that for valid vts, no `Job` will actually be run, so we'll still need to fall back to registering the `runtime_classpath` path for valid vts somewhere - keeping on doing it where it's currently done is as good a place as any.",{},{}
