10640,IssuesEvent,2018-06-21 17:58:06+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,356399,asvetlov,7049303,aio-libs,closed,HTTPException should retain cause information,[],[],1,"## Long story short

I would like to use a pattern like:
```python
try:
    do_something()
except SomeException as e:
    raise HTTPInternalServerError(reason='My message') from e
```
with cause information retained. Does it make sense to implement `HTTPException.__bool__()` to always `True`?

## Expected behaviour

Two tracebacks separated by `The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception:`

## Actual behaviour

The cause information is lost, because `traceback.TracebackException` evaluates the [truthiness of the exception value](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/de86073a761cd3539aaca6f886a1f55effc0d9da/Lib/traceback.py#L464) to determine whether cause lines are produced. For `HTTPException`, [truthiness is resolved](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/7cf5785f5383ee67756d0f8d86ea3516b823b940/aiohttp/web_response.py#L426) via `StreamResponse.__len__()` which returns 0.

## Steps to reproduce

<!-- Please describe steps to reproduce the issue.
     If you have a script that does that please include it here within
     markdown code markup -->

## Your environment

<!-- Describe the environment you have that lead to your issue.
     This includes aiohttp version, OS, proxy server and other bits that
     are related to your case. 
     
     IMPORTANT: aiohttp is both server framework and client library.
     For getting rid of confusing please put 'server', 'client' or 'both'
     word here.
     -->
",{},{}
10646,IssuesEvent,2017-04-22 21:36:28+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,598990,fafhrd91,7049303,aio-libs,closed,bools in params are treated differently from bools in formdata,"[{'id': 58986080, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aio-libs/aiohttp/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff', 'default': True}]",[],7,"## Long story short

When using the `ClientSession.post` method, 
both the url parameters and form post data can be passed as a dictionary.
In the url parameter dictionary you cannot pass boolean values, while you can in the form dictionary.


## Expected behaviour

I expect both the form and url parameter encoding to behave in a similar way,
so passing a boolean in a url parameter dict will be converted to a string ""True"" or ""False"".

## Actual behaviour

Instead i get an exception:

    Invalid variable type: mapping value should be str or int, got True

Traceback:
 * `yarl/__init__.py`  line 737 in `with_query`
 * `aiohttp/client_reqrep.py` line 71, in `__init__`

## Steps to reproduce

```python
import asyncio
import aiohttp


client = aiohttp.ClientSession()

async def trypost(urlparam, formparam):
    try:
        response  = await client.post(""http://example.com/"", params={""urlparam"":urlparam}, data={""formparam"":formparam})
        response.close()
        print((urlparam, formparam), ""->"", response)
    except Exception as e:
        print((urlparam, formparam), ""->"", e)

tasks = [
        trypost(""true"", True),
        trypost(True, ""true""),
]

loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
loop.run_until_complete(asyncio.gather(*tasks))

client.close()
```

## Your environment

I am using aiohttp v2.0.7

",{},{}
