11462,IssuesEvent,2017-12-28 04:00:59+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,2070843,geekpete,6764390,elastic,opened,Current docs for Curator source install list missing/404 urls for dependencies,"[{'id': 186818252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/elastic/curator/labels/Documentation', 'name': 'Documentation', 'color': '009800', 'default': False}]",[],0,"On the source install page in the docs:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/client/curator/current/python-source.html

A number of urls for dependencies are not working.


### Expected Behavior
URLs listed should resolve to downloadable tarballs rather than a HTTP 404.

### Actual Behavior
URLs are coming back as 404s due to either removed/missing tarball or possibly altered path to the file on the remote site.

### Steps to Reproduce the Problem

Go to:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/client/curator/current/python-source.html

try the urls for the listed dependencies and some fail:

- https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/u/urllib3/urllib3-1.20.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
    - https://github.com/shazow/urllib3/archive/1.20.tar.gz
    - https://pypi.python.org/packages/ee/11/7c59620aceedcc1ef65e156cc5ce5a24ef87be4107c2b74458464e437a5d/urllib3-1.22.tar.gz#md5=0da7bed3fe94bf7dc59ae37885cc72f7



- https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/c/click/click-6.7.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
  - https://pypi.python.org/packages/95/d9/c3336b6b5711c3ab9d1d3a80f1a3e2afeb9d8c02a7166462f6cc96570897/click-6.7.tar.gz#md5=fc4cc00c4863833230d3af92af48abd4
  - https://github.com/pallets/click/archive/6.7.tar.gz


- https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.1.23.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
    - https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.01.23.tar.gz
    - https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.11.05.tar.gz


- https://codeload.github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/tar.gz/5.4.1
  - possible alternates:
    - https://pypi.python.org/packages/78/76/502a8e76e60d1fb3bf8326d94001465db8b7a4dd4df6c70b6f8ab3d87e33/elasticsearch-5.5.1.tar.gz#md5=91e0ddaf8952ef371005e9c6696b2f67
    - https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/archive/5.5.1.tar.gz

## Detailed Description
Potentially listed Install urls could be regularly tested to detect if they're not returning a valid url.
The equiv detail contained in the requirements.txt could be documented on this page to show minimum versions for a particular Curator version and potentially all dependency versions that have been tested as working with a particular Curator version.
",{},{}
11468,IssuesEvent,2015-07-22 19:04:48+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,465041,TinLe,6764390,elastic,closed,"curator v3.2.0 reporting successful indices deletion, but does not actually deleted them","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/elastic/curator/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ff0040'}]",[],23,"I have a cluster with bunch of old indices that I want to prune, keeping only latest 7 days.  I run the command.

$ curator --port 9217 --timeout 900 delete indices --timestring ""%Y.%m.%d"" --older-than 7 --time-unit days
2015-06-25 16:54:49,038 INFO      Job starting: delete indices
2015-06-25 16:54:49,628 INFO      Pruning Kibana-related indices to prevent accidental deletion.
2015-06-25 16:54:49,628 WARNING   Very large list of indices.  Breaking it up into smaller chunks.
2015-06-25 16:54:49,629 INFO      Deleting indices as a batch operation:
.....bunch of outputs
2015-06-25 16:55:33,241 INFO      Job completed successfully.

But that is not true.   I checked and there are still many indices that were supposed to be deleted and were not.   So if I run the same command multiple times, eventually all the indices get deleted.

The output of multiple runs is fairly long, I'll put them in a gist here:
https://gist.github.com/TinLe/c64dbe495e0c2d228a6b

The last few runs correctly gave Error or Warnings, so that part is correct.   The error/warning were because the cluster just started creating new daily indices, so were busy with initializing shards (yellow status).   Once the cluster got done with the new indices, the deletion completed fine.   When I started the deletion, the cluster was relatively quiet and in green status.

The bug is that curator is reporting ""Job completed successfully"" when obviously that is not the case.

",{},{}
11471,IssuesEvent,2016-12-29 17:25:30+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,6436143,jakommo,6764390,elastic,closed,Filter Element timestring can substring match incorrectly:  example %Y.%W matches %Y.%m%.d,[],[],5,"During configuration of curator with multiple types of timestamped index names we encountered a case in which the timestring of %Y.%W would unexpectedly match an index with a %Y.%m.%d timestring.  Is it possible to add an anchor or option for an anchor to the timestring regex to more accurately match in these cases?
",{},{}
