11670,IssuesEvent,2015-04-14 07:20:30+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,189798,jirikuncar,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,celery: deprecation warnings issue,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_major', 'name': 'p_major', 'color': 'e11d21'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_bug', 'name': 't_bug', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],4,"## Abstract
We use pickle as the serialization method when communicating with celery. This method will be disabled in future standard configurations because it has security issues. We should decide how to move on.

## Problem description

Celery starts to emit the following warning:
 ```
Starting from version 3.2 Celery will refuse to accept pickle by default.

The pickle serializer is a security concern as it may give attackers
the ability to execute any command.  It's important to secure
your broker from unauthorized access when using pickle, so we think
that enabling pickle should require a deliberate action and not be
the default choice.

If you depend on pickle then you should set a setting to disable this
warning and to be sure that everything will continue working
when you upgrade to Celery 3.2::

    CELERY_ACCEPT_CONTENT = ['pickle', 'json', 'msgpack', 'yaml']

You must only enable the serializers that you will actually use.


  warnings.warn(CDeprecationWarning(W_PICKLE_DEPRECATED))
```

## Possible solutions
We should solve this by implementing one of the following solutions.

### a) pickle
Follow the given advice and set the `CELERY_ACCEPT_CONTENT` config variable. If so, we should update the documentation to reflect this and we must mention that the broker should be secured on the network side. The pickle method has some serious security problems because it enables remote code execution.

### b) something else
Switch over to a slower but more secure method, e.g. `msgpack` (which is kind of JSON but in binary form and faster, see [msgpack.org](http://msgpack.org/)). This would solve the security problem but we have to evaluate the performance impact.

## Importance and suggestion
It does not seem that celery 3.2 is close yet. The broker should be secured anyway, but ""executing any task"" and ""executing any code"" is a quite different security level. So we might want at least go for solution a). The documentation does not describe the security impact of unsecured worker configurations right now (or I didn't see it).",{},{}
11676,IssuesEvent,2016-07-04 13:00:38+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,189798,jirikuncar,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,More visible alert subscription box,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_WebAlert', 'name': 'c_WebAlert', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_minor', 'name': 'p_minor', 'color': 'f7c6c7'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_enhancement', 'name': 't_enhancement', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],2,"Originally on 2012-02-01

The WebAlert module (along with RSS subscription) is one of those useful features that users are not always aware of. It would be good to make it more visible, for eg. by advertising the subscription box at the top of search results pages. See attached mockups using a tooltip next to search box. 

Given that subscribing to alerts is not a frequent task, this contextual help should only be displayed to a given user for a limited time only (displayed X times, or only for 48 hours, or until the user ""closed"" the help), just enough to make the user aware of the feature, and provided that he is instructed on how to use the feature after the tooltip has disappeared.

Ideally this kind of contextual help would be generalized to other cases where we want to make users aware of some feature on a given page (""Did you know...?""). If centrally managed (WebHelp module?), such a system would help to launch advertisement/training campaigns of existing/new features, and ensure that such hints would remain unobtrusive (eg. just one tooltip displayed per day/week/month).

If such a framework is implemented, it would also be useful to offer the possibility to insert tooltips that are opened at user request, when clicking on a help anchor (eg `[?]`).",{},{}
