12153,IssuesEvent,2016-12-01 16:07:37+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,Warning not filtered as supposed to,[],[],1,"The warning emitted for missing standard script name in [py36compat.py](https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/blob/master/setuptools/command/py36compat.py#L76) is not suppressed by [`manifest_maker.warn`](https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/blob/master/setuptools/command/egg_info.py#L558) but seems to be supposed to.

I found this while exploring a setup.py as a directory containing a `__main__.py`.  I happened to run

```
python setup.py/__main__.py
```

and I had a warning about the file `__main__.py` missing.

You can suppress the warning by using the `script_name` keyword argument of `setuptools.setup` like so:

```
from setuptools import setup

setup(
    name=""mypackage"",
    # ... a plethora of other kwargs
    script_name=""setup.py""
)
```
",{},{}
12156,IssuesEvent,2017-04-18 23:06:16+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,reopened,Updating MANIFEST.in does not correctly update the package sdist creates,"[{'id': 349315096, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pypa/setuptools/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}, {'id': 349315320, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pypa/setuptools/labels/major', 'name': 'major', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}]",[],8,"Originally reported by: **spookylukey (Bitbucket: [spookylukey](http://bitbucket.org/spookylukey), GitHub: [spookylukey](http://github.com/spookylukey))**

---

The behaviour of sdist depends on previous contents of MANIFEST.in, not just the current. This is not fixed even by running `setup.py clean` or `setup.py clean --all` (although this should not be necessary).

This is very surprising behaviour, and potentially dangerous too - if someone accidentally adds a MANIFEST.in rule that includes a file that must not be distributed and notice the problem, they would expect that removing the rule will remove the file, but it does not.

I've attached a bash script that demonstrates the problem.

---
- Bitbucket: https://bitbucket.org/pypa/setuptools/issue/436
",{},{}
12166,IssuesEvent,2017-01-07 18:11:50+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,self test problems,[],[],3,"I wanted to run the self tests for setuptools (using the pypi distfile), but had a couple of problems:

* `setup.py test` complains about `error: invalid command pytest`

* next I tried using `pytest`, but that reported 18 errors, all having to do with `pkg_resources.tests` not being found.

* finally, I tried `tox`, but that complained about a missing  `tox.ini` 

Additionally, I think that relying on `tox` (or `pytest`) for the tests is not a good idea, since both of these need `setuptools` for installation.",{},{}
12171,IssuesEvent,2016-05-04 19:22:43+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,314716,astrofrog,647025,pypa,opened,Passing --user option to easy_install when called programmatically,[],[],0,"I am using an application which doesn't expose the Python interpreter and only an IPython console, so I want to install packages from inside IPython. To do this, I thought the easiest way would be:

```
In [1]: from setuptools.command import easy_install

In [2]: easy_install.main(['numpy', '--user'])
```

However, this doesn't work, as it seems to want to interpret all items in the list as a package name:

```
SystemExit: error: Not a URL, existing file, or requirement spec: '--user'
```

Is there an easy way to pass the ``--user`` flag to the ``easy_install`` command in this way?
