12369,IssuesEvent,2017-05-09 14:23:50+00:00,27082457,HIPS/autograd,15261883,j-towns,7935606,HIPS,opened,Verifying test coverage of vjps,[],[],0,"@duvenaud has mentioned a couple of times that it would be good to set up coverage checking, to make sure there aren't any primitives which are not covered by our tests. I agree this is quite important. The tests should fail if a vjp that is defined is not at least executed at some point during tests.

The current standard tool for checking test coverage is [coverage.py](http://coverage.readthedocs.io/en/latest/). This tool is well integrated into nose and straightforward to use, and I've used it to find some typos in Autograd. However it isn't sufficient for the above, because it only checks whether _lines_ have been executed during testing.

Most of Autograd's grads are defined by something of the form
```python
name_of_primitive.defvjp(lambda some_args: gradient_function, argum=...)
```
This line will be executed when the module it's in is imported, regardless of whether the lambda function is ever called. So how can we test whether that grad is actually called?

One option would be to switch to using `def ...` instead of using `lambda`s to define vjp functions, however I think this is out of the question since it would be a lot of effort and mean way more lines of code.

Off the top of my head I can't think of a more practical way to do this, I'm raising this in case anyone else has any ideas.",{},{}
