12568,IssuesEvent,2017-02-03 22:07:28+00:00,53438969,globus/globus-cli,6742946,tuecke,6120321,globus,opened,config help,[],[],0,"The only way I could figure out what the various ""config"" commands do was to play with it.  The help text wasn't much help.

The ""globus config -h"" text should probably say that the config file is used to store various config parameters such as access tokens automatically, but that there are some config options that the user can set to configure the default behavior of the CLI.  Then list those user-definable options (e.g., cli.output_format).

It was not clear from the ""config init"" help that it would interactively prompt me to set user-definable configuration values, namely for output_format.  But is the ""config init"" even needed?  It seems redundant with ""config set"", aside from its interactive nature.  But I suppose if there are more user-definable options, that would be useful.

Perhaps have a common example that you use across all of the config help messages.  For example, in ""config set"" show how to set cli.output_text to json.  In ""config remove"", show how to remove the cli.output_text.  In ""config show"", show how to show the cli.output_text.
",{},{}
12573,IssuesEvent,2016-04-13 18:45:49+00:00,53344710,globus/globus-sdk-python,1300022,sirosen,6120321,globus,closed,Improving response classes,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/globus/globus-sdk-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/globus/globus-sdk-python/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],4,"I find myself constantly forgetting to add the `.data`, and it seems superfluous. I think it's especially confusing for the iter responses. I propose that we add a `__getitem__` to `GlobusResponse` that operates on the `.data`, so you can do `response['path']` instead of `response.data['path']`, and make it have a default `__next__` that directly exposes `response['DATA']`. That makes it more convenient, while still giving us a central response class that we can tweak in the future if needed.

With the current response formats, it feels like Java, not like Python.",{},{}
