14111,IssuesEvent,2018-08-07 12:16:25+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,opened,conda 4.5.10 behavior change regarding solver selection of packages with features,"[{'id': 670135778, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw2NzAxMzU3Nzg=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/deprecation_or_behavior_change', 'name': 'deprecation_or_behavior_change', 'color': 'fb7777', 'default': False}, {'id': 572951183, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1NzI5NTExODM=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source-core', 'name': 'source-core', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 311005392, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwzMTEwMDUzOTI=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/tag-solver', 'name': 'tag-solver', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 404647916, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MDQ2NDc5MTY=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type-discussion', 'name': 'type-discussion', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],0,"In conda 4.5.9 via #7601 we added a feature flag to disable a solver rule that minimized the number of packages in an environment not having active features.  That is, given that a feature is active in an environment, the rule sought to maximize the selection of packages that relied on that feature.  For example, if `debug` was an active feature in an environment, the rule is designed to choose every debug package possible.  This solver rule has been in place since conda 4.0.

Recently, the rule has led to issues with two isolated but widely impactful use cases.

Some six months ago, the Anaconda team patched `defaults` metadata to remove `vc` from the `features` key of packages, and instead use direct dependency relationships. This is the preferred pattern going forward. However, conda-forge (or any channel hosted on anaconda.org) does not have a workable method for patching package metadata short of removing and rebuilding the package.  Therefore conda-forge is still using the old vc pattern whereby the vc version variant of a package is described in the `features` key.  The result is that a change in channel priority, either moving from `defaults` to `conda-forge` or vice versa, will needlessly switch out the majority of the python packages in the environment.

While the `vc` problem affects only Windows users, users on all platforms are potentially affected by a similar problem regarding blas implementations.  For example, see https://github.com/conda/conda/issues/7548.

The @conda/conda-core team has deliberated on this issue, and we are strongly considering releasing conda 4.5.10 with the feature flag `featureless_minimization_disabled_feature_flag` introduced in #7601 toggled from a default value of `false` to a default value of `true`.  This will effectively change the default behavior of the solver regarding packages with features that has been present since conda 4.0.  We do not make this decision lightly.

The alternative is to wait for the release of conda 4.6.0 to toggle the default value of this feature switch.  In the last several years, the conda project has established a well-developed [canary process](https://www.anaconda.com/blog/developer-blog/what-conda-canary/) in which major feature releases, as 4.6.0 will be, transition through beta and rc builds published to the `conda-canary` channel over a six-plus week period.

While the core team is still soliciting feedback, we feel that the accumulated urgency warrants swift action, justifying the behavior change in a rapid patch release.

To test the proposed conda 4.5.10 behavior for yourself, run `conda info` to ensure you're currently using conda 4.5.9, and execute

    conda config --set featureless_minimization_disabled_feature_flag true

The current plan is to publish conda 4.5.10 to the `conda-canary` channel today, followed by publication in `defaults` 48-72 hours later.",{},{}
14112,IssuesEvent,2015-08-14 08:43:33+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,3067425,ikalev,6392739,conda,opened,h5py >=2.4.0 not detected by pip/setuptools,[],[],0,"I'm trying to build a conda package which depends on ``h5py``. Here's a fragment from my ``meta.yaml`` recipe:

```
build:
  binary_relocation: true
  number: 0
  script: python setup.py install
package:
  name: xyz
  version: 0.2.1
requirements:
  build:
  - h5py 
  - python
  run:
  - h5py 
  - python
source:
  path: C:\source
test:
  requires: []
```

When I try to build this package, setuptools does not detect that ``h5py`` is already installed in the build environment and the build fails:

```
c:\> conda build c:\recipe
...
Processing dependencies for xyz==0.2.1
Searching for h5py

RuntimeError: Setuptools downloading is disabled in conda build. Be sure to add all dependencies in the meta.yaml  url=https://pypi.python.o
rg/simple/h5py/r
```

It works fine if I change the requirement to ``h5py <=2.3``. But since version 2.4 h5py can't be detected by pip or setuptools:

```
C:\>conda create -n bug pip
C:\>activate bug

[bug] C:\>conda install h5py=2.3
[bug] C:\>pip install h5py
Requirement already satisfied (use --upgrade to upgrade): h5py in c:\anaconda\envs\bug\lib\site-packages

[bug] C:\>conda install h5py=2.4
[bug] C:\>pip install h5py
Collecting h5py
  Using cached h5py-2.5.0.tar.gz
```

This might be the case because ``conda install h5py=2.3`` installs ``h5py-2.3.1-py2.7.egg-info`` in ``site-packages``, but this directory is missing if you install ``h5py >=2.4``.",{},{}
14118,IssuesEvent,2015-04-11 21:31:09+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,632049,cjw296,6392739,conda,opened,safety check of total dependencies at the end of an install,[],[],0,"Of course, having proper, full, dependency resolution before the ""install"" of a package or set of packages commits to being completed would be what we should aim for, in the meantime:

once any install operation completes, do a check of the installed packaged and make sure none of their dependency version specifications have been violated and whine loudly if they have!

(another one for @tswicegood )",{},{}
