14886,IssuesEvent,2018-08-21 22:51:02+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,23153234,retke,23690422,Cog-Creators,opened,[V3] Be able to have global settings and data (not instance-specific),[],[],0,"# Feature request

<!-- This template is for feature requests. Please fill out the following: -->


#### Select the type of feature you are requesting:

<!-- To check a box, replace the space between the [] with a x -->

- [ ] Cog
- [ ] Command
- [x] API functionality

#### Describe your requested feature

<!--
Feel free to describe in as much detail as you wish.

If you are requesting a cog to be included in core: 
    - Describe the functionality in as much detail as possible
    - Include the command structure, if possible
    - Please note that unless it's something that should be core functionality,
      we reserve the right to reject your suggestion and point you to our cog 
      board to request it for a third-party cog
      
If you are requesting a command:
    - Include what cog it should be in and a name for the command
    - Describe the intended functionality for the command
    - Note any restrictions on who can use the command or where it can be used

If you are requesting API functionality:
    - Describe what it should do
    - Note whether it is to extend existing functionality or introduce new functionality
   
-->

Currently, the 3rd party cogs are always specific and depending to one single instance. The data is stored in the instance's files and cannot ""interact"" with other instances. An option to get a global data path would be great and reduce disk usage/memory usage/CPU usage for specific functions of some cogs.

Currently, `redbot.core.data_manager.cog_data_path()` returns something like this: `InstanceName/cogs/YourCog/`. Adding another function like `global_data_path` which would lead to `/usr/local/share/Red-DiscordBot/YourCog/` (on Linux) would be great for hosting something that use a lot of disk usage for example.

As an example, with that feature, the Audio cog could download Lavalink.jar in that global folder (I host 4 bots, only one Lavalink server but still 4 identic files) and make shared Lavalink server easier.",{},{}
14895,IssuesEvent,2018-05-07 22:26:48+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,22035876,mikeshardmind,23690422,Cog-Creators,opened,[V3] Cog vs extension management,[],[],0,"# Feature request

#### Select the type of feature you are requesting:

- [ ] Cog
- [X] Command
- [ ] API functionality

#### Describe your requested feature
There should be a simple way to view (and unload if wanted) all loaded cogs, not just extensions.

Right now, cogs can load additional cogs. This might seem like an undesirable behavior at first, but it has a large number of legitimate uses if properly paired with `__unload` functions which would remove them afterwards.

However, it can also lead to undesirable behaviors that a user would have no indication of without reading through all cogs they had installed or digging through certain bot properties using dev tools.

While it is still the user's responsibility to only install things they trust, there should be a way to view all loaded cogs without requiring a command such as:
```
[p]debug "", "".join(bot.cogs.keys())
```
As this is not available in the core bot (you need to use the `--dev` flag, and this also isn't an intuitive solution.)

Here's a gist to a mediocre example of the details of the problem (The details in the gist are intentionally largely missing, but there's enough there to detail a potential problem)
https://gist.github.com/mikeshardmind/248e0f49db47f148fcbce58643a10373
",{},{}
14899,IssuesEvent,2018-02-12 20:53:59+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,20862007,aikaterna,23690422,Cog-Creators,opened,[V3] Downloader errors out on existing repo name conventions,[],[],0,"### Type:

- [X] Suggestion
- [ ] Bug

### Brief description of the problem
Downloader will error out when given a repo name that contains dashes, like ""aikaterna-cogs"", when adding a repo. 

### Expected behavior
v3 Downloader should behave like v2 Downloader and allow a dash in repo names.
v3 Downloader specifically says in its help string: ""Name can only contain characters A-z, numbers and underscore"" but I feel like this should be addressed for ease of use with existing conventions.

### Actual behavior
Downloader will show `[p]repo add` command help instead of adding the repo.

### Steps to reproduce
1. Add a repo with a dash in the repo name
2. Type ""I agree"" to agree to the repo addition
3. Bot will display help message for repo add and not add the repo
",{},{}
