15046,IssuesEvent,2016-06-11 19:43:31+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,closed,spinel: external headers should not be included by core spinel protocol,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/NCP', 'name': 'NCP', 'color': 'c2e0c6'}]",[],4,"Embedded platforms may not have access to this header or the in6_addr structure included by spinel.h:

[spinel.h]
```
 #include <arpa/inet.h>
// ...
typedef struct in6_addr spinel_ipv6addr_t;
```

Perhaps moving over to using openthread-types.h would be more appropriate?

```
#include <openthread-types.h>
// ...
typedef otIp6Address spinel_ipv6addr_t;
```",{},{}
15050,IssuesEvent,2017-01-12 19:16:28+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,7153743,pvanhorn,16142269,openthread,opened,DataRequest Poll Timer can become stuck,[],[],0,"The logic in HandlePollTimer and SendMacDataRequest is such that it is possible for the mPollTimer to not be re-started when it should.

If SendMacDataRequest exits with error kThreadError_Already because a DataPoll is already in the SendQueue then the poll timer will not be re-started and the system will not continue to periodically poll.

The solution should likely have all the timer restart logic inside HandlePollTimer() rather than splitting it between that method and SendMacDataRequest.",{},{}
15052,IssuesEvent,2017-04-25 06:54:54+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,2240212,bukepo,16142269,openthread,closed,How to tell if OpenThread is alive,"[{'id': 355043113, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],0,"CC2538's serial port often fails to respond, both on Linux and Windows, both with CP210x and FTDI usb-to-serial driver. And there is no easy way to tell if the device is working correctly. I suggest OpenThread periodically call a platform API to tell platform that OpenThread is working normally, so that the platform can implement their own way to show the status of OpenThread, e.g. blinking LED when idle, LED on when handling data, etc.
",{},{}
