15741,IssuesEvent,2015-01-06 07:03:34+00:00,27086567,scrapinghub/dateparser,1576126,RajatGoyal,699596,scrapinghub,opened,Wrong date parsing when year changes,[],[],0,"During scraping a [website](http://www.dzone.com/links/index.html) I encountered this issue:

Dec 14 11:00 is parsed as datetime.datetime(2015, 12, 14, 11, 0) whereas it was supposed to mean datetime.datetime(2014, 12, 14, 11, 0) because it was a post of 2014.

I think there should be parameter like *only_allow_past_dates* which should disable future date parsing and interpret it only as the date that has passed. ",{},{}
15742,IssuesEvent,2016-06-16 07:07:52+00:00,27086567,scrapinghub/dateparser,1888537,waqasshabbir,699596,scrapinghub,closed,Day/month/year order for different locales,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/scrapinghub/dateparser/labels/easy', 'name': 'easy', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/scrapinghub/dateparser/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],8,"We should specify what day/month/year order is prefferable for different languages.
We can use [this information](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Date_format_by_country) as a starting point and define `date_order = DMY` for each language in our file (don't forget to add a specific validation for this). Then, based on this info we should pass [proper arguments](https://labix.org/python-dateutil#head-b95ce2094d189a89f80f5ae52a05b4ab7b41af47) to dateutil parser.",{},{}
