16216,IssuesEvent,2018-07-24 01:50:23+00:00,71932349,ray-project/ray,21118851,simon-mo,22125274,ray-project,opened,redis-server(s) are not secured ,[],[],0,"Ray's redis servers are not secured. 

Out of all the [security features](https://redis.io/topics/security/#authentication-feature) outline by redis, it is most sensible to implement a basic [authentication feature](https://redis.io/topics/security/#authentication-feature) and enable it by default. 

I can help implement it. But I was wondering *what is the most efficient way to implement it in ray without touching too much code path?*

I'm currently thinking:
- Add an argument in `ray.init(redis_password=None)`, we can generate a password if possible.
- In `start_redis` (of `services.py`) start the redis process with flag `--requirepass <PASSWORD>`
- Store the password in `ray.experimental.global_state` for ease of access

Please give feedback! Thanks!",{},{}
