17687,IssuesEvent,2017-04-14 15:53:56+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,closed,Certbot-auto and 3rd party plugins,"[{'id': 277078963, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%203rd%20party', 'name': 'area: 3rd party', 'color': 'c7def8', 'default': False}, {'id': 276243379, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%20certbot-auto', 'name': 'area: certbot-auto', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 281347824, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/has%20pr', 'name': 'has pr', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],5,"As reported by @gboudreau in #4020, because `certbot-auto` recreates the venv every time it upgrades, it removes any 3rd party Certbot plugins that may have been installed here. This is rude.

Easiest and most straight forward fix is to upgrade the existing venv rather than creating a new one.",{},{}
17698,IssuesEvent,2016-05-10 01:11:15+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,479213,pde,17889013,certbot,closed,./letsencrypt-auto --help doesn't print help but starts installing sw without asking,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'bfd4f2'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/letsencrypt-auto', 'name': 'letsencrypt-auto', 'color': '00a080'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/ui%20/%20ux', 'name': 'ui / ux', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],3,"I just watched an otherwise-interested user trying to get started with letsencrypt decide the whole project was not trustworthy after having it start installing packages when asked to print usage information via (as shown in the `README`) `./letsencrypt-auto --help`. This is very bad initial UX. The `--help` option should work as documented (without modifying anything about the system it's run on) and there should either be a strong warning in the `README` that `letsencrypt-auto` invokes the system package manager to install packages, or it should interactively request permission to do so when run without arguments.
",{},{}
