17710,IssuesEvent,2018-07-01 08:46:09+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,359622,zh99998,17889013,certbot,opened,docker image with long running process,[],[],0,"currently official certbot docker images are all run one-shot. it exits after cert obtain finished.

it's really inconvenience since docker don't have a cron function and system crontab is uncomfortable when deploying to container orchestration systems.

my solution is wrap by a simple shell script loop run certbot and sleep.

```bash
#!/bin/sh

while :
do
  certbot $@
  sleep 30d
done
```
it works but I have to make my own docker image just because of this.
since it's a common behavior and totally no my own custom logic, I think certbot should get it into official docker image maybe with a tag (like certbot/certbot:cron, certbot/dns-cloudxns:cron)",{},{}
17731,IssuesEvent,2018-04-26 09:27:59+00:00,95603860,vmware/container-service-extension,22272895,A1Dox,473334,vmware,opened,Documentation clarification re: cse check,[],[],0,"Could we modify the wording of [Step 4 of the install guide](https://github.com/vmware/container-service-extension/tree/master/docs#4-validate-configuration) to highlight the fact that cse check needs to validate the actual install. I know it follows the install step, but the current wording suggests it checks the configuration file rather than the installation. How about:

>### 4\. Validate successful installation.
>
>Validate the configuration was installed successfully with:
>```shell
>$ cse check --config config.yaml
>```",{},{}
